76561198101115250,Recommended,262450,18777293,"Posted: 30 October, 2015",all,greytrek19,"Now, I've had to change my review because, to their credit, the developer more-or-less fixed my initial key complaint in their biggest patch, namely in the balance of the special traits. Unfortunately, as time has gone on, other complaints have replaced this one, even if they're not QUITE enough to merit another thumbs-down. I'll detail them here so that buyers can make an informed choice. If you'd like details on how the game actually plays, the descriptions and some other reviews/threads should give you the gist.Needless to say, the lack of multiplayer is one gaping flaw, although it should be noted that a good chunk of the player abilities would have to be disabled or revamped for this to work, since some of them do too much to cancel out others to make for consistently balanced matches. And there's no point allowing players to see each other's selections beforehand, since this would just lead to a cyclical bout of power-switching as they keep trying to counteract the other's selections. Still, doing this would make multiplayer perfectly doable.The next complaint is that there is an incredible need for some kind of counter or image to give the player at least some idea of how many cards are currently in the discard pile, which is currently off-screen. Some players can apparently keep track of this mentally without disrupting their experience, but the rest of us often have no idea what to expect once the pile starts to get low, and when choosing whether to take from the discard pile or do something else, it would be nice to be able to tell whether there were many - or even any - cards in the pile altogether.And the final gripe is that, as much as people dismiss the mere suggestion, I think there is some genuine unfairness in the AI's knowledge of the draw deck. I don't think it's deliberate stacking or cheating, but rather a partial failure to partition what the AI SHOULD know (i.e., nothing) from what it actually does. I base this on the sheer number and proportion of cases in which the AI will take unreasonably high risks (namely drawing when it already has four, five, or even six cards on the table and the chance of a bust is high, even though there is nothing protecting most or all of the current cards from loss in the event of a bust) only to be rewarded with exactly the right card or even succession of cards it needs to get the most out of its current hand. I understand the effects of luck, but this particular bit of grand (and situationally specific) ""fortune"" has played out a few too many times for me to be satisfied with that explanation. Combine this with the AI's being generally aware of what's in the discard pile (unlike the player), and there are times when what should have been a fair bout turns into an infuriating, unbroken string of losses for a perfectly completent player. Now, to be fair, the program does sometimes make less-than-efficient or even self-defeating plays thanks to other holes in the programming, and luck does indeed play its role in all cases, so this doesn't really break the game. But it sure makes for a less enjoyable experience than it might have been.Still, for a cheap, renewable diversion, you could do worse."
